  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a felony in most jurisdictions, including the United States. Money laundering involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by transferring it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. The purpose is to make the money appear as if it comes from a legitimate source.\n\nIn the United States, money laundering is a federal crime under the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986** (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957). Penalties for money laundering can include:\n\n- **Fines**: Individuals can face fines of up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction, whichever is greater.\n- **Imprisonment**: Offenders can receive sentences of up to **20 years** in federal prison per count.\n- **Asset Forfeiture**: Authorities may seize assets involved in or derived from the money laundering scheme.\n\nAdditionally, money laundering is often prosecuted in conjunction with other crimes, such as drug trafficking, fraud, or terrorism financing, which can lead to even harsher penalties.\n\nOutside the U.S., most countries have similar laws criminalizing money laundering, often as part of international efforts to combat organized crime and terrorism financing. Penalties vary by jurisdiction but are typically severe.",
